{
  "id": "integrating-polynomials",
  "title": "Integrating Polynomials",
  "order": 10,
  "estimatedMinutes": 8,
  "conceptTags": ["antiderivative", "definite_integral"],
  "published": true,
  "steps": [
    {
      "id": "ip-step-1",
      "type": "read",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Integration runs differentiation in reverse, and it splits over sums in exactly the same way. To integrate a polynomial, integrate each term on its own and add the results — the sum rule again."
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\int \\big(f(x) + g(x)\\big)\\,dx = \\int f(x)\\,dx + \\int g(x)\\,dx",
          "display": true
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Each term uses the reverse power rule: add 1 to the exponent, then divide by the new exponent. So $x^2 + x$ integrates to:"
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\int (x^2 + x)\\,dx = \\int x^2\\,dx + \\int x\\,dx = \\frac{x^3}{3} + \\frac{x^2}{2}",
          "display": true
        }
      ],
      "feedback": { "correct": "", "incorrect": "", "hint": "" }
    },
    {
      "id": "ip-step-2",
      "type": "drag_drop",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Integrate term by term — reverse the power rule on each. Drag the antiderivative of each term into the blanks to build $F(x)$ for $f(x) = x^3 + x^2 + x$."
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "x^3 + x^2 + x",
          "domain": [-2, 2],
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "static": true
        },
        "answer": {
          "type": "drag_drop",
          "prefix": "F(x) =",
          "blanks": [
            { "accept": "\\frac{x^4}{4}" },
            { "accept": "\\frac{x^3}{3}" },
            { "accept": "\\frac{x^2}{2}" }
          ],
          "bank": [
            "\\frac{x^4}{4}",
            "\\frac{x^3}{3}",
            "\\frac{x^2}{2}",
            "\\frac{x^3}{2}",
            "\\frac{x^2}{3}",
            "\\frac{x^4}{3}"
          ]
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Right — reverse the power rule on each: $x^3 \\to \\frac{x^4}{4}$, $x^2 \\to \\frac{x^3}{3}$, and $x \\to \\frac{x^2}{2}$, so $F(x) = \\frac{x^4}{4} + \\frac{x^3}{3} + \\frac{x^2}{2}$.",
        "incorrect": "Add 1 to each exponent, then divide by that new exponent.",
        "hint": "$x^n \\to \\frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}$, so $x^2 \\to \\frac{x^3}{3}$ (divide by the new exponent, 3)."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ip-step-3",
      "type": "read",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "One subtlety: an antiderivative isn't unique. The derivative of any constant is 0, so you can tack any number onto $\\frac{x^3}{3}$ and it still differentiates back to $x^2$. That means $\\frac{x^3}{3}$, $\\frac{x^3}{3} + 1$, and $\\frac{x^3}{3} - 7$ are all antiderivatives of $x^2$."
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\frac{d}{dx}\\left(\\frac{x^3}{3} + C\\right) = x^2 \\quad \\text{for any constant } C",
          "display": true
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "To capture the whole family at once, we add a constant of integration $C$. An integral with no limits — an indefinite integral — stands for every antiderivative together:"
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\int x^2\\,dx = \\frac{x^3}{3} + C",
          "display": true
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "So the very first example is, more precisely, $\\int (x^2 + x)\\,dx = \\frac{x^3}{3} + \\frac{x^2}{2} + C$ — a single $C$ covers the constant for the whole sum."
        }
      ],
      "feedback": { "correct": "", "incorrect": "", "hint": "" }
    },
    {
      "id": "ip-step-4",
      "type": "multiple_choice",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Which expression represents every antiderivative of $f(x) = 3x^2$ — the full indefinite integral $\\int 3x^2\\,dx$?"
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "hintAfterAttempts": 1,
        "answer": {
          "type": "multiple_choice",
          "options": ["$x^3 + C$", "$x^3$", "$3x^3 + C$", "$6x + C$"],
          "correctIndex": 0
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Right — $\\frac{d}{dx}(x^3) = 3x^2$, and the $+ C$ captures every antiderivative at once.",
        "incorrect": "Reverse the power rule to find one antiderivative, then add $C$ to include all of them.",
        "hint": "$3x^2 \\to x^3$ (raise the exponent, divide the coefficient by it), then write $+ C$: $x^3 + C$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ip-step-5",
      "type": "read",
      "conceptTag": "definite_integral",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "To evaluate a definite integral, the Fundamental Theorem says: find an antiderivative $F$, then subtract its values at the endpoints, $F(b) - F(a)$. For polynomials, $F$ comes straight from the reverse power rule."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Here the constant of integration doesn't matter: it's the same at both endpoints, so it cancels — $(F(b) + C) - (F(a) + C) = F(b) - F(a)$. That's why definite integrals never need a $C$."
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\int_0^2 (2x + 1)\\,dx = \\big[x^2 + x\\big]_0^2 = (4 + 2) - 0 = 6",
          "display": true
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Here $F(x) = x^2 + x$ is an antiderivative of $2x + 1$, and evaluating it from 0 to 2 gives 6."
        }
      ],
      "feedback": { "correct": "", "incorrect": "", "hint": "" }
    },
    {
      "id": "ip-step-6",
      "type": "numeric",
      "conceptTag": "definite_integral",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Your turn. Use the antiderivative $F(x) = x^2 + x$ to evaluate this integral as $F(3) - F(0)$."
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\int_0^3 (2x + 1)\\,dx",
          "display": true
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "2*x + 1",
          "domain": [0, 4],
          "yDomain": [0, 9],
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 0,
          "initialSlider": 3,
          "static": true
        },
        "hintAfterAttempts": 1,
        "answer": { "type": "numeric", "value": 12, "tolerance": 0.1 }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Exactly — $F(3) - F(0) = (9 + 3) - 0 = 12$.",
        "incorrect": "Evaluate $x^2 + x$ at 3 and at 0, then subtract.",
        "hint": "$F(3) - F(0) = (9 + 3) - 0 = 12$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ip-step-6b",
      "type": "slider_graph",
      "conceptTag": "definite_integral",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "The lower limit doesn't have to be 0. Find the value of $t$ for which this integral equals 10, then drag the slider there."
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\int_1^t (2x + 1)\\,dx = 10",
          "display": true
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "2*x + 1",
          "domain": [0, 4],
          "yDomain": [0, 9],
          "sliderLabel": "t",
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showSecant": false,
          "showValue": false,
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 1,
          "showAreaValue": false,
          "areaReadoutMath": true,
          "integrand": "(2x + 1)",
          "sliderMin": 1,
          "sliderMax": 3.5,
          "sliderStep": 0.1,
          "initialSlider": 1
        },
        "hintAfterAttempts": 1,
        "answer": { "type": "slider", "value": 3, "tolerance": 0.15 }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Nice — $(t^2 + t) - 2 = 10$ gives $t^2 + t - 12 = 0$, so $(t - 3)(t + 4) = 0$ and $t = 3$.",
        "incorrect": "Set $(t^2 + t) - 2 = 10$ and solve for $t$, then drag the slider there.",
        "hint": "$t^2 + t - 12 = 0 \\to (t - 3)(t + 4) = 0 \\to t = 3$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ip-step-7",
      "type": "slider_graph",
      "conceptTag": "definite_integral",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "The shaded region is the area under $f(x) = x + 1$ from 0 to $t$. Find the value of $t$ for which this area equals 4, then drag the slider there."
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\int_0^t (x + 1)\\,dx = 4",
          "display": true
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "x + 1",
          "domain": [0, 4],
          "yDomain": [0, 5],
          "sliderLabel": "t",
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showSecant": false,
          "showValue": false,
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 0,
          "showAreaValue": false,
          "areaReadoutMath": true,
          "integrand": "(x + 1)",
          "sliderMin": 0,
          "sliderMax": 4,
          "sliderStep": 0.5,
          "initialSlider": 0
        },
        "hintAfterAttempts": 1,
        "answer": {
          "type": "slider",
          "value": 2,
          "tolerance": 0.2
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Nice — $\\frac{1}{2}t^2 + t = 4$ gives $t^2 + 2t - 8 = 0$, so $(t - 2)(t + 4) = 0$ and $t = 2$.",
        "incorrect": "Set $\\frac{1}{2}t^2 + t = 4$ and solve for $t$, then drag the slider there.",
        "hint": "$\\frac{1}{2}t^2 + t = 4 \\to t^2 + 2t - 8 = 0 \\to (t - 2)(t + 4) = 0 \\to t = 2$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ip-step-8",
      "type": "power_term",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Coefficients ride along here too. Build an antiderivative of $f(x) = 6x^2$ — use the steppers to set the coefficient and exponent of $F(x)$."
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "6*x^2",
          "domain": [0, 2],
          "yDomain": [0, 24],
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 0,
          "initialSlider": 1,
          "static": true
        },
        "hintAfterAttempts": 1,
        "answer": {
          "type": "power_term",
          "coefficient": 2,
          "exponent": 3,
          "startCoefficient": 6,
          "startExponent": 2,
          "previewPrefix": "F(x) ="
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Right — raise the exponent to 3, then divide the coefficient by it: $6x^2 \\to 6 \\cdot \\frac{x^3}{3} = 2x^3$. Differentiate $2x^3$ to check: back to $6x^2$.",
        "incorrect": "Add 1 to the exponent, then divide the coefficient by that new exponent: $6x^2 \\to \\frac{6}{3}x^3$.",
        "hint": "Exponent $2 \\to 3$, then $6 \\div 3 = 2$, giving $2x^3$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ip-step-9",
      "type": "read",
      "conceptTag": "definite_integral",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "You can now run calculus in both directions on any polynomial: differentiate term by term with the power rule, or integrate term by term with the reverse power rule — adding a constant of integration $C$ for an indefinite integral — and with the Fundamental Theorem, turn those antiderivatives into exact areas."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Derivatives, integrals, and the theorem that unites them — that's the heart of calculus. Nice work making it through!"
        }
      ],
      "feedback": { "correct": "", "incorrect": "", "hint": "" }
    }
  ],
